1. What this file is
--------------------

This document keeps a short installation and build summary for this fork.
It is intentionally practical and does not try to mirror all upstream ReactOS
documentation.

This repository is a personal fork of ReactOS centered on the current 0.5.x
line and on a day-to-day workflow of experimenting, studying the codebase and
retouching the system toward the maintainer's preferred behavior.


2. Build environment
--------------------

For this fork, use the ReactOS Build Environment (RosBE) before running build
commands.

Canonical local build pattern:

  cmd.exe /c "call C:\RosBE\RosBE.cmd && ninja -C F:\SavanDev\reactos\output-MinGW-i386 <target>"

The usual validation artifact for this fork is:

  ninja -C F:\SavanDev\reactos\output-MinGW-i386 bootcd

General upstream RosBE information is available here:

  https://reactos.org/wiki/Build_Environment


3. Building
-----------

A broader ReactOS build guide can be found at:

  https://reactos.org/wiki/Building_ReactOS

In this fork, the common cases are:

3.1 Building binaries

Run the desired Ninja target from the configured build directory.
Examples:

  ninja -C F:\SavanDev\reactos\output-MinGW-i386 win32k
  ninja -C F:\SavanDev\reactos\output-MinGW-i386 bootcd

3.2 Building a bootable CD image

Run:

  ninja -C F:\SavanDev\reactos\output-MinGW-i386 bootcd

This creates the bootable CD image used for VM validation in this fork.


4. Installation
---------------

By default, ReactOS can only be installed on a machine that has a FAT16 or
FAT32 partition as the active (bootable) partition. The partition on which
ReactOS is to be installed (which may or may not be the bootable partition)
must also be formatted as FAT16 or FAT32. ReactOS Setup can format the
partitions if needed.

Starting with 0.4.10, ReactOS can also be installed using BtrFS. Treat that as
experimental.

ReactOS can be installed from source output or from the bootable CD image.

4.1 Installation from sources

If you do not have an existing ReactOS installation you want to upgrade, build
`bootcd`, boot from the generated image, and follow Setup.

If you already have an installation you want to update, `ninja install` will
create a `reactos` directory containing the installed tree. Copy its contents
over the target installation.

If you do not want to copy files manually on every update, set the
`ROS_INSTALL` environment variable first.

On Windows:

  set ROS_INSTALL=c:\reactos

On Linux:

  export ROS_INSTALL=/mnt/windows/reactos

Then run:

  ninja -C F:\SavanDev\reactos\output-MinGW-i386 install

4.2 Installation from bootable CD image

Build `bootcd`, boot from the resulting image, and follow Setup.


5. Validation notes
-------------------

For this fork, visible system behavior matters more than abstract build
completeness. Boot, logon, shell, repaint, input, storage and shutdown paths
should be checked after meaningful changes.

See these documents for the current fork direction:

  README.md
  TECHNICAL_DIRECTION.md
  ROADMAP_0.5.0.md
  STABILITY_VALIDATION.md
  PERSONAL_WORKFLOW.md


6. Upstream references
----------------------

For upstream ReactOS project information, bug reporting and community links,
see:

  https://reactos.org/
